{"key":"post-9521139","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9521139</id>\n<content>The reason they get on the tops of the caps is aerodynamics.&amp;nbsp; The spores are shaped similar to an airplane wing and ejected from the basidia with extreme force.&amp;nbsp; The actually do a 180 and then often settle on the tops of the caps.&amp;nbsp; Next time, harvest sooner.&amp;nbsp; Your mushrooms will be of higher quality and taste much better.&amp;nbsp; I like to pick them before the veil tears and the cap has even opened yet.&amp;nbsp; This is the stage they're at their best, just like the button mushrooms you get in the grocery store.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9524720</next>\n<prev>9521085</prev>\n<first>9513819</first>\n<last>9524923</last>\n<when>1230702257</when>\n<utime>12/31/08 07:44 AM</utime>\n</post>"}